---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Trolley Case Study | Ross Lyall Portfolio"
  description="Case study for Trolley, a private household grocery planning app."
>
  <div class="page-shell">
    <main>
      <section class="case-hero case-hero--trolley">
        <a class="back-link" href="/">← Back to portfolio</a>

        <p class="eyebrow">Case Study / Home App</p>
        <h1>Trolley</h1>
        <p class="case-hero__lead">
          A private household grocery planning app that turns weekly meals into
          a structured shopping list, helping make food planning, shopping and
          household extras easier to manage.
        </p>

        <div class="case-meta">
          <span>React</span>
          <span>Supabase</span>
          <span>Vercel</span>
          <span>PWA</span>
          <span>Private household app</span>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-showcase">
        <div class="mock-browser">
          <div class="mock-browser__bar">
            <span></span>
            <span></span>
            <span></span>
          </div>

          <div class="mock-screen" style="background: var(--trolley);">
            <span class="mock-screen__label">Trolley dashboard</span>
            <h2 class="mock-screen__heading">
              Meals become a shopping workflow.
            </h2>

            <div class="mock-ui-grid">
              <div class="mock-ui-card"></div>
              <div class="mock-ui-card"></div>
              <div class="mock-ui-card"></div>
              <div class="mock-ui-card mock-ui-card--wide"></div>
              <div class="mock-ui-card"></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="mock-phone">
          <div class="mock-phone__screen">
            <div class="mock-phone__pill"></div>
            <div class="mock-phone__button">Plan meals</div>
            <div class="mock-phone__button">Review list</div>
            <div class="mock-phone__button">Start shopping</div>
            <div class="mock-phone__button">Add extras</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-overview">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">The problem</p>
          <h2>
            Weekly shopping was too dependent on memory, messages and guesswork.
          </h2>
        </div>

        <div class="case-copy">
          <p>
            Trolley was built around a real household problem: planning meals,
            remembering what was needed, adding extra items during the week and
            then turning all of that into a usable shopping list.
          </p>

          <p>
            A normal notes app or shared list can work for simple shopping, but
            it does not understand meals, portions, regular items, household
            members, review stages or the difference between planning and
            actually walking round a shop.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-overview">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">The solution</p>
          <h2>
            A meal-driven planner that creates a proper shopping workflow.
          </h2>
        </div>

        <div class="case-copy">
          <p>
            The app lets meals be planned across the week, then generates a
            shopping list from the products attached to those meals. Items can
            be reviewed, adjusted, moved, skipped or marked as bought.
          </p>

          <p>
            It is designed as a practical family tool rather than a generic demo
            app: it includes household members, extras, shopping mode, custom
            items and phone install support.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">Key features</p>
          <h2>What Trolley does</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="feature-grid">
          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>01</span>
            <h3>Meal planning</h3>
            <p>
              Plan meals by day, slot and household member, with support for
              shared dinners and different meals where needed.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>02</span>
            <h3>Generated shopping lists</h3>
            <p>
              Turn a selected planning period into a structured list based on
              meal ingredients and saved product data.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>03</span>
            <h3>Review mode</h3>
            <p>
              Check and adjust the generated list before shopping, including
              quantities, products and custom extras.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>04</span>
            <h3>Shopping mode</h3>
            <p>
              Mark items as bought, skipped or unavailable, with category-based
              sections and shop-friendly controls.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>05</span>
            <h3>Extras</h3>
            <p>
              Add one-off household items during the week so they are pulled
              into the next generated shopping list.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>06</span>
            <h3>Phone install</h3>
            <p>
              Built as a PWA so it can be installed on phones and used like a
              lightweight private household app.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-overview">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">Design thinking</p>
          <h2>The app follows the way shopping actually happens.</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="case-copy">
          <p>
            The workflow is split into stages because planning, reviewing and
            shopping are different jobs. A meal planner needs more detail, while
            shopping mode needs simple, fast actions that work well on a phone.
          </p>

          <p>
            The design also avoids making every item equal. Products have
            categories, preferred shopping locations, notes and future support
            for portion-to-purchase conversion.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">What I learned</p>
          <h2>Useful lessons from building it</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="lesson-list">
          <article>
            <h3>Data structure matters early</h3>
            <p>
              The app became much more powerful once products, meals, list
              items, extras and household members were treated as separate parts
              of the system.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article>
            <h3>Mobile workflows need fewer decisions</h3>
            <p>
              Shopping mode needed to be simpler and more direct than the
              desktop planning screens.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article>
            <h3>Real users reveal the awkward bits</h3>
            <p>
              The app improved most when it was tested against actual household
              behaviour rather than an ideal version of how planning should
              work.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-next">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">Future improvements</p>
          <h2>Where Trolley could go next</h2>
        </div>

        <ul>
          <li>Inventory tracking for household staples and cat food.</li>
          <li>Smarter portion-to-purchase conversion.</li>
          <li>Reorder reminders for online and bulk purchases.</li>
          <li>Better long-term analysis of buying patterns.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>
    </main>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
